<TEXT>
the philippines with its 30 billion debt 
may be the next country to get help from banks under pressure to 
help the third world climb out of poverty international finance 
sources say 
mexico got first attention under treasury secretary nicholas f 
bradys debtreduction plan that countrys annual debt payments 
could be reduced by as much as 3 billion under a financial package 
announced july 23 
brazil and argentina owe a lot more than the philippines 120 
billion and 60 billion but sources say they will have to wait 
the new argentine government of president carlos menem is still 
settling in and brazil will have an election in november 
another candidate for early help is venezuela where president 
carlos andres perez wants his countrys 35 billion debt cut in 
half there has been pressure for action on venezuela because of 
bloody riots in february caused by austerity measures taken by the 
government to help meet its payments 
it is uncertain how much can be done for the philippines as it 
is for mexico despite the plan to reduce that countrys 54 billion 
debt the success of the mexico plan depends on bankers 
willingness to participate experts say 
now the arrangement has been agreed for mexico therell be a 
question of reducing debt and interest for the philippines too 
said a banker who spoke on condition of anonymity 
much will depend on how much pressure the bush administration 
exerts on banks to work out an agreement with the philippines as 
it did on the mexico debt problem the banker said 
one calculation is that the philippines needs 17 billion in 
new money over the next two years 
for the philippines one expert who also spoke on condition of 
anonymity predicted that an accord could be reached by the end of 
august between that countrys government and a committee of 12 
banks led by manufacturers hanover trust co a meeting is due in 
new york by midaugust 
however haywood fleisig in charge of philippine affairs at the 
world bank said any action by commercial bankers would affect only 
about 75 billion of that countrys debt 
individual governments to which the philippines also owe money 
have already granted some relief in may the governments put off 
for six years any repayment of principal and threequarters of the 
interest on 185 billion due them 
incomes in the philippines as in many african and latin 
american countries have declined during much of the 1980s 
president corazon aquino said last week the philippine situation 
is getting better although 500000 people have crossed the poverty 
line since she took office three years ago the average filipino 
earned about 590 in 1987 according to the world bank 
venezuela has long been a richer country than either mexico or 
the philippines because of its oil resources nearly all its 
borrowing has been from commercial banks rather than from 
governments or official bodies 
but a committee of bankers chaired by chase manhattan corp 
refused venezuelas debtreduction proposal last week and more 
meetings are due in august 
