<TEXT>
repairs to the governments three 
tritiumproducing nuclear reactors will take longer and will cost 
more than four times the previous estimate a newspaper reported 
today 
in december the energy department estimated that repairs at the 
savannah river site in south carolina would cost 350 million and 
be completed in 1990 
but a confidential report submitted to the department on june 26 
by the westinghouse savannah river co said the project will cost 
at least 166 billion and wont be completed until 1991 the new 
york times reported 
the complexs three reactors are the nations sole source of 
tritium a shortlived radioactive gas essential for many nuclear 
weapons because tritium decays to inert helium the tritium charge 
must be renewed from time to time 
energy secretary james d watkins planned to announce on tuesday 
a fiveyear plan to bring all of the nations nuclear weapons 
production plants into compliance with environmental and safety 
laws the washington post reported today 
under the proposal the department would spend 24 billion next 
year and up to 37 billion in each of the following four years 
watkins told the post the plan would include management of 
hazardous waste and restoration of the environment around the 
plants 
the three reactors at savannah river have been shut for more 
than a year because of safety and management concerns during the 
shutdown the previous contractor du pont corp withdrew and the 
government hired the westinghouse electric corp subsidiary to 
operate the plant 
the energy department pays for operation of the plant and the 
additional money will come from the departments budget 
the confidential report calls for restarting the first reactor 
in september 1990 the second in december 1990 and the third in 
february 1991 the times said 
jack herrmann spokesman for westinghouse savannah river said 
the company has submitted plans to the department proposing a 
timetable and cost estimates for restarting the reactors 
the plans he said present a number of variables and a number 
of options at this point its an interim process with doe were 
not really in a position to comment because theres a lot of give 
and take in this process 
westinghouse presented a restart plan for the idled kreactor to 
the department on june 26 and supplemental plans for restarting the 
other two reactors on july 10 herrmann said 
herrmann said the department and westinghouse have held 
discussions about the plans off and on the last several weeks 
but there has not been a formal resolution 
experts with the energy department told the times that 
recovering tritium will not be possible until nine months after a 
reactor has been turned on 
this means that the first new supplies will not be available 
until june 1991 defense officials have said some weapons might 
have to be cannibalized to keep other weapons in service if tritium 
production isnt restarted soon 
in addition the plan calls for operating the reactors at half 
their potential power because of concerns about the ability of 
their emergency cooling systems to withstand accidents the times 
said 
in a letter accompanying the plan james s moore president of 
westinghouse savannah river said the delay and extra cost were a 
result of initial difficulties engineers had in understanding the 
magnitude of the changes needed to make the reactors safe 
according to the times 
