<TEXT>
followers of santeria went to federal court today 
to challenge a ban on animal sacrifice arguing the practice is 
integral to their afrocuban religion 
jorge duarte a lawyer for the church of the lukumi babalu aye 
said the hialeah city ordinance violates followers freedom of 
religion 
but an attorney for the city countered that the ordinance is a 
permissible effort to regulate the killing of animals and disposal 
of their bodies 
there is a legal governmental need for prevention of cruelty 
to animals and prevention of disease said richard garrett 
animals are being left throughout the city 
he also told us district judge eugene p spellman that the 
sight of smeared blood causes children to be more violent 
as many as 25000 people in south florida are followers of 
santeria whose rites include the killing of chickens birds and 
goats as offerings to the gods 
three city ordinances passed in 1987 ban the ritual sacrifice or 
slaughter of any living creature violations carry a fine of 500 
or 60 days in jail 
duarte who is being assisted by the american civil liberties 
union compared santeria rites with jewish dietary laws that are 
protected under federal and state law 
</TEXT>
