<TEXT>
new yorkers with aids and related illnesses will 
need 7 billion in health and social services over the next 4 
years a task force said monday 
the new york city aids task force predicted that by the end of 
1993 4990 acutecare hospital beds onefifth of the citys 
total will hold aids patients 
the money is needed to double the number of hospital beds 
nursing home beds and housing units for aids patients as well as 
to provide outpatient longterm and home health care said dr 
stephen c joseph task force chairman and city health commissioner 
the report also calls for greatly expanded prevention programs 
including aids education in all grades it calls for elimination of 
waiting lists for treatment of drug abusers many of whom are 
exposed to aids by sharing needles it urges that people with aids 
and related illnesses should be treated by communitybased 
organizations whenever possible and says those organizations 
should get more money from the private and public sectors 
the 29member task force includes government and private medical 
experts and representatives of business and aids support groups 
its recommendations arent binding but the report will be used as 
a lobbying tool and a blueprint for public and nonprofit agencies 
joseph said 
as of june 30 there were 20177 aids cases reported in new york 
city according to the federal centers for disease control in 
atlanta 20 percent of the national total of 99936 cases 
by the end of 1993 the report said the cumulative total in the 
city may reach 63952 aids cases and perhaps 50157 deaths 
the report says it appears that people with aids are surviving 
longer partly due to earlier diagnosis and better treatment 
studies are urgently needed to predict their needs it says 
special services should be developed for teenagers a group 
where the disease is likely to increase silently but quickly in 
the years to come the report warns 
leaders of minority groups were urged to heighten awareness of 
the disease in their communities the mentally retarded and 
mentally ill also must be taught how to avoid the virus the report 
said 
</TEXT>
