<TEXT>
a congressional commission will soon condemn the 
secretly signed nazisoviet pact that gave the three baltic 
republics to the soviet union a legislator said monday 
the kremlin has denied existence of the secret section of the 
molotovribbentrop pact for 50 years although it long has been 
accepted in the west 
the 26member panel of the soviet congress of peoples deputies 
is expected to vote this week on a report acknowledging existence 
of the agreement said one of its members estonian legislator igor 
n gryazin 
he said in an interview the commission will publish the 
agreement and declare it null and void 
the agreement is at the heart of a drive by people in latvia 
lithuania and estonia for more control over their own affairs if 
not outright independence 
soviet history books long have claimed that latvia lithuania 
and estonia voluntarily joined the union of soviet socialist 
republics at the beginning of world war ii baltic activists say 
the secret protocol is evidence they were forced to do so 
gryazin said the final report does not take an even more radical 
step demanded by many baltic activists that of saying that the 
protocol paved the way for the 1940 soviet takeover gryazin said 
instead it says stalinist methods of foreign policy became 
possible due to this protocol according to the legislator 
still gryazin said weve done a good job if you think that 
from a period of total denial to acceptance has been just three 
weeks of commission meetings 
president mikhail s gorbachev supported the creation of the 
parliamentary commission in june but implied western copies of the 
secret protocol might be forgeries however the kremlin clearly 
supports the findings because the commission is chaired by 
gorbachev ally and ruling politburo member alexander n yakovlev 
and includes valentin m falin head of the international 
department of the communist party central committee 
hundreds of baltic dissidents have been jailed over the years 
for protesting the pact named for the men who signed it the soviet 
foreign minister vyacheslav molotov and his german counterpart 
joachim von ribbentrop 
but under gorbachevs more tolerant approach toward dissent 
thousands of baltic residents have demonstrated regularly against 
the pact which new more liberal estonian and lithuanian 
governments in may asked the kremlin to renounce unofficial 
political groups in latvia have made similar calls 
major demonstrations are scheduled in the three republics on 
aug 23 the 50th anniversary of the pact 
newspapers in all three republics published the pact a year ago 
and it appeared in june in a smallcirculation monthly questions 
of history 
gryazin said the commission on the political and legal 
evaluation of the 1939 sovietgerman nonaggression pact expects to 
publish its report this week with an authenticated version of the 
pact in the masscirculation national press for the first time 
before the full congress votes on it 
the draft report calls on the 2250member congress scheduled 
to meet in october to declare the pact legally null and void 
and an aberration from leninist principles which 
contradicted the sovereignty and independence of a number of third 
states the third states are latvia lithuania and estonia which 
were independent between the two world wars and poland 
baltic parliaments decided to join the soviet union in 1940 but 
activists and many historians say this was done under pressure the 
united states and several other western nations describe the 
baltics as enslaved nations and never have recognized their 
incorporation into the soviet union 
gryazin said it is important to realize that if we want to be 
in the soviet union we want to have some guarantee that the soviet 
union denies such forceful methods and accepts democratic forms 
of federation 
he predicted baltic residents will see the report as approval 
of an elementary fact and other skeptical soviets will become 
convinced though it will be a shock for them 
gryazin a law professor said the parliamentary commission 
obtained 55 pounds of documents and a copy of the protocol from the 
us library of congress 
