an appeals court on monday unanimously upheld 
the convictions and sentences of three young men who took part in 
the 1986 howard beach attack in which a black man fleeing a white 
gang was hit by a car and killed 
in doing so the court affirmed the trial judges ruling that 
defense attorneys like prosecutors may not use peremptory 
challenges to exclude jurors on the basis of race 
a message loud and clear must go forth that racial violence by 
any person or group whatever their race will not be tolerated by 
a just and civilized society and that when it does occur it must 
be appropriately punished wrote the five justices from the state 
appellate division in brooklyn 
in the first decision the three defendants had argued that the 
evidence introduced at their trial did not justify their 
convictions and that certain confessions were tainted and should 
have been suppressed 
but the justices disagreed 
defense attorneys also had objected to a ruling by the trial 
judge justice thomas demakos that limited them in barring blacks 
from the jury 
demakos cited a us supreme court ruling that prosecutors could 
not use peremptory challanges to exclude jurors on the basis of 
race the high court ruling did not specifically say whether 
defense attorneys could do the same 
the appeals court said the ruling did not affect the outcome of 
the trial since the only black juror seated as a result of the 
ruling was excused before deliberations 
scott kern 20 jon lester 20 and jason ladone 18 were 
convicted in december 1987 of seconddegree manslaughter and 
firstdegree assault for attacking three black men in the howard 
beach section of queens on dec 20 1986 one of the black men 
23yearold michael griffith was struck by a car and killed as he 
fled 
another man cedric sandiford was beaten with a baseball bat 
and tree limbs 
lester was sentenced to 15 to 30 years in prison kern received 
a six to 18year term and ladone was sentenced to five to 15 
years kern and ladone had their sentences stayed pending the 
appeal lester who was sentenced to one to three years in prison 
on an unrelated prior conviction for weapons possession is in jail 
this is a precedent said charles l weintraub a lawyer for 
the three defendants the supreme court has never said that this 
applies to defense lawyers 
he said he would ask the court of appeals the states highest 
court to hear the case 
