<TEXT>
prices farmers received for raw products 
dropped 07 percent from june to july but were up 28 percent from 
a year ago the agriculture department said monday 
the departments agricultural statistics board said in its 
preliminary report that decreases in the prices for oranges 
broilers soybeans and corn were partially offset by higher prices 
for potatoes cotton tomatoes and hogs 
prices of cattle potatoes milk and lettuce contributed most 
to the increase over a year ago lower prices for soybeans corn 
apples and oranges were partially offsetting the report said 
the july index of prices paid for commodities and services 
interest taxes and farm wage rates was 178 percent of its 1977 
average the index was was 06 percent above april of this year and 
35 percent above july of last year 
higher prices during july for feeder cattle and calves 
gasoline and building materials were partially offset by lower feed 
prices the report said 
net cash income of farmers according to agriculture department 
economists is expected to fall 5 percent to 14 percent this year 
to a range of 50 billion to 55 billion from the record 1988 level 
of 58 billion 
net cash income is the amount farmers have to spend during the 
year and represents the difference between gross cash income and 
cash expenses cash income rose last year despite drought partly 
because of higher market prices and crops farmers had stored from 
previous harvests 
the decline this year is expected to stem from farmers larger 
cash expenses as they boost plantings and also because of lower 
federal subsidies 
consumer food prices are forecast by usda to rise an average of 
4 percent to 7 percent this year following a 41 percent increase 
in 1988 
based on the preliminary figures the price index for livestock 
and livestock products as a group declined 06 percent from june to 
july but still averaged 61 percent above last years figure 
overall crop prices declined 29 percent from last month and 22 
percent from july 1988 
the all fruit index was down 20 percent from last month and 19 
percent from a year ago 
most of the decrease from last month was due to declining 
prices for oranges and strawberries the report said the only 
fruits in the index showing an increase in prices were lemons and 
peaches 
the report said 
the midjuly corn price of 243 per bushel was 9 cents lower 
than june while oats declined 17 cents to 165 per bushel 
barley averaged 221 per bushel down 12 cents from last month 
soybeans were 675 per bushel down 31 cents from june this 
year and a drop from 850 a year ago 
cattle averaged 6760 per 100 pounds of live weight 
nationally the same as last month and up from 6320 a year ago 
those are the averages for all types of cattle sold as beef 
hogs averaged 46 per 100 pounds up from last months 4510 
and 4410 in july 1988 
eggs on the norm were 566 cents per dozen a 1 percent 
increase from last months 556 cents and last years 495 cents 
broilers were 391 cents per pound in july down 35 cents from 
julys 426 cents and last years 415 
