<TEXT>
philipp brothers inc a new yorkbased 
commodity futures trading concern and three affiliates have agreed 
to pay a record 4 million in penalties to settle allegations of 
fraud in cocoa futures contracts federal regulators said monday 
philipp brothers is a whollyowned subsidiary of the wall street 
investment firm salomon inc but federal officials said present 
management at salomon was not involved in any alleged wrongdoing 
this is by far the largest civil penalty ever imposed by this 
commission said dennis klejna director of enforcement for the 
commodity futures trading commission 
the cftc which regulates us futures markets charged in a 
19count administrative complaint that philipp brothers and others 
engaged in several deceptive practices including the ractice of 
bucketing 
in bucketing a broker misrepresents trades by buying or selling 
futures contracts off the floor of a futures exchange while 
telling the customer the trades were made on the exchange 
in the current case the cftc charged philipp brothers told 
customers their trades were being handled on the coffee cocoa and 
sugar exchange in new york when the trades actually were handled 
on the exchange floor 
klejna said brokers who use the practice may avoid paying fees 
to the exchange 
customers never really held a futures position on the 
exchange said klejna they thought they did when in fact they 
had orders that were booked at the firm 
the customer nevertheless was required to pay the same 
commissions fees and margin collateral deposited to buy futures 
charged for properly executed transactions and positions 
according to the complaint 
about 100000 cocoa futures were bought or sold in this manner 
carrying commission fees of about 16 each or a total of 165 
million said klejna 
philipp bros said in a statement that the activities were 
inititally brought to the attention of the cftc by the present 
management of philipp bros as a result of an internal 
investigation current management subsequently cooperated 
thoroughly with the cftc 
klejna said one reason the fine was so large is that the alleged 
violations went on so long from july 1981 through september 1984 
the commission also alleged philipp brothers and others entered 
into improper prearranged trades and fictitious sales and failed 
to accurately prepare order tickets 
the affiliates phibro corporation and philipp brothers 
commodities corp both of new york and cocoa merchants ltd of 
london settled the allegations without admitting or denying 
guilt said klejna 
in addition to the companies five former employees of philipp 
brothers were charged in the complaint and have not yet settled 
with the cftc named by the commission were anthony hd weldon of 
london daniel f tulig of sparta nj peter gilliam of surrey 
england esther lander greenfield of monsey ny and mark 
glowatz of east meadow ny 
</TEXT>
