<TEXT>
many rural hospitals are losing money because 
their costs are too high not because medicare reimbursements are 
too low a government report concluded monday 
the report by the inspector general of the department of health 
and human services dismissed the belief by many in the hospital 
industry that the governments payment for medicare patients is 
jeopardizing the financial health of hospitals particularly those 
in rural areas 
hhs inspector general richard kusserows report said his 
offices study found rural hospitals that achieved a profit on 
medicare patients had lower costs than comparable hospitals with 
losses in the program 
in 1987 the most recent year for which data is available 956 
rural hospitals or 43 percent earned medicare profits while 1255 
rural hospitals or 57 percent had medicare losses 
since all the rural hospitals received about the same medicare 
revenues per patient the key difference was their costs per 
patient the report said 
nonprofitable rural hospitals are unable to make profits from 
treating medicare patients because their costs are too high the 
report concluded 
in our opinion unprofitable rural hospitals should not look 
to the medicare program for financial salvation the report said 
the report said rural hospitals losing money under medicare tend 
to be smaller than their profitable counterparts have fewer beds 
lower occupancy more staff per occupied bed and keep patients 
longer 
rep thomas tauke riowa cochairman of the rural health care 
coalition disagreed with the inspector generals conclusion 
saying rural hospitals are desperately working to keep their 
costs low and still are struggling 
its very clear that the current medicare formula is working 
against them tauke said historically rural hospitals have 
kept their costs down and as a result they are being penalized by 
the current system 
the hhs report said federal officials should encourage rural 
hospitals to consolidate with other underutilized facilities and 
to convert excess beds to other uses 
in the short run hospital administators must turn to such 
costcontrolling measures as ensuring that they keep patients in 
the hospitals no longer than necessary and employ only the number 
of staff members required to provide appropriate patient care 
the report said 
</TEXT>
