the house monday approved a 16 billion 
measure to pay for operations of the legislative branch in the 
coming year after making a minimal trim in its own electionyear 
mailing expenses 
the bill which now goes to the senate would provide about 125 
million for house mailing expenses over the coming year an 
increase of 130 percent from the current years figure of 54 
million 
this bill is a bit of an embarrassment said rep bill 
frenzel rminn mailing is the last black hole of congress 
frenzel said lawmakers are increasingly abusing their mailing 
privileges to ensure their reelections rather than simply 
responding to mail from home 
very few people ask for our newsletters so we mail them to 
everybody he said they dont write us and so we buy lists and 
send personal unsolicited first class letters to people who never 
communicated with us 
the bill pays for salaries of congressional staff members 
office expenses and related agencies like the library of congress 
and capitol police force for the year beginning oct 1 it did not 
include senate expenses estimated to total some 450 million 
which will be added when the measure goes to the other side of the 
capitol 
lawmakers voted 39210 to reduce from six to four the number of 
districtwide postal patron newsletters each house member can mail 
in each twoyear term but they left a loophole that permits 
continued unlimited mailings of notices for town hall type 
meetings 
frenzel said those mailings are being abused 
some of the meetings only attract two to ten people but the 
notices are mailed to 200000 people its a device to put their 
names in the mailbox and increase their name recognition he said 
rep vic fazio dcalif chairman of the appropriations 
subcommittee which produced the bill agreed mailing has become a 
problem but he said he was reluctant to curb what is for some 
lawmakers their primary means of communicating with constituents 
the house also adopted by 4058 an amendment by rep tim 
penny dminn to cut 10 million from the mailing account but 
such a move means little since congress routinely overspends its 
mailing account and adds money later to make up the deficit 
they also approved on a voice vote language requiring that 
massmailed newsletters be postmarked at least 60 days before an 
election that would eliminate the practice of lastminute 
newsletters that become tangled in production backlogs and end up 
being mailed by incumbents during the height of campaign season 
the house rejected by 246167 an effort by frenzel to cut 97 
million from the bill which would have held the growth in 
congressional spending to about the rate of increase in the rest of 
the government 
