<TEXT>
as napoleon iii reshaped parts of 
paris mussolini an area of rome and stalin the center of moscow 
so too has nicolae ceausescu redesigned bucharest romanias 
capital 
in just five years 19 churches a synagogue and hundreds of 
private homes have vanished from the citys centuriesold center 
victims of a vision of grandeur now nearing completion 
on aug 23 a national holiday marking the 45th anniversary of a 
successful uprising against a pronazi government ceausescu and 
his wife elena will formally open the palace of the people a 
white stone structure of vastly surreal proportions topped by a 
triangular metal flagpole 
from this 20thcentury fortress the ceausescus will rule their 
land and watch over the top government and communist party offices 
housed in the palace 
the palace faces on the boulevard of the victory of socialism a 
threemile avenue that cuts defiantly through the old city center 
it is there according to ceausescus plans government and party 
officials who are now sequestered in cozy villas will inhabit 
40000 apartments in stylish 10story buildings they have risen 
in just four years and are now complete with groundfloor shops 
that stock luxury goods for purchase only by foreign delegations 
elaborate fountains play along the center of the avenue 
popularly called the boulevard of the victory of bankruptcy 
but behind the empty gleaming buildings wires hang out of 
walls bulldozers and cranes are at work and the whole project has 
an unfinished air that suggests it will not be ready for full 
habitation by aug 23 
at the 18thcentury antim monastery nestled behind the gleaming 
white buildings the synodical library looks oddly out of place 
bishop nifon of the the romanian orthodox church explained the 
building was moved a few yards so it could be preserved but not 
interfere with the new civic center 
he said a few churches not of too much historical 
importance were destroyed for the project while at least eight 
others have been moved so that they are now hidden behind the new 
buildings 
this reorganization of the landscape is going on throughout 
bucharest as well as the rest of romania 
city centers that grew centuries now contain heaps of rubble and 
dozens of impersonal new towers of concrete that outwardly fulfill 
the universally propagated ideal of transforming romania into a 
modern industrial society 
four settlements around bucharest have literally been wiped off 
the map according to western diplomats 
but travel throughout romania suggests to foreigners and 
diplomats that most of the 8000 villages designated for absorption 
into larger agroindustrial centers under a scheme to 
systematize the countryside will not be destroyed but simply 
slide into decay 
there had been fears in the west and particularly in hungary 
that thousands of such villages would be bulldozed under 
ceausescus plan 
in cities the modernization drive has destroyed hundreds of 
villas deemed too bourgeois in appearance for modern romania an 
estimated 40000 residents of the capital were moved to make way 
for the giant new civic center 
there are some benefits to the vast building program 
bucharest a city of 25 million now has a subway that anybody 
can use for just 10 cents as an alternative to usually jammed 
trolley cars and buses 
an artificial lake and swimming pool complex also have been 
built near one of bucharests endless highrise residential areas 
