<TEXT>
once those who could afford them invariably chose antiques over 
reproductions nowadays when the best original design is often 
unavailable too expensive the wrong dimensions or too fragile 
the reproduction can be the better choice 
this change in thinking is due to a variety of factors for one 
thing many reproductions now have more accurate finishes so they 
dont stick out like a sore thumb when mixed with antiques that 
means mixing a little old with a lot of new is a good method of 
getting the right look less expensively 
second an eclectic room is considered more desirable than the 
completely accurate period room that was once was fashionable 
comfort has become more important than historical accuracy for many 
people 
few decorators would hesitate to use plushly upholstered but 
anachronistic seating in a historic room especially since there 
really was no comfortable american upholstery in the 18th century 
according to decorator stanley hura 
in the dining room an extension table of modern origin is often 
a necessity and in the traditional bedroom or family room that 
lacks closets installing a modern wall system may be the only 
solution hura for example recently placed a floortoceiling 
wall system in an american traditional bedroom for needed storage 
space he gave the unit a builtin look by installing molding 
around it he said 
when combining old and new furniture of more than one style a 
few precautions can prevent the pieces from clashing with one 
another 
certain styles even though from different periods look good 
together says hura for example japanese shaker and scandinavian 
modern combine well english regency and chinese furniture work 
together the rounded forms of the 18thcentury french pieces and 
art nouveau and victorian also marry well 
if youre furnishing a formal victorian room and need storage 
remember that armoires are in character with that style if you 
have contemporary lacquered cabinetry add oriental or art deco 
accessories and reproductions at the windows you might choose 
pleated shades or shoji screens simple regency chairs would not be 
out of place in this room 
the forms of the pieces dictate how they combine you could 
mix a 17thcentury italian table and chairs and contemporary 
furniture and lamps because the lines work well together hura 
says 
doityourself decorators can learn their own taste preferences 
by studying decorating books and magazines 
the most appealing homes are the ones where people put 
together what they love the accurate period room is for museums 
not for living says hura 
one of the marks of an interesting room is the unexpected 
touches it contains especially in the form of accessories 
according to fran laufer who imports unusual accessories colorful 
and exotic items are in demand for example relatively affordable 
indian paintings on fabric known as pichwais and burmese 
embroideries are being selected by those seeking distinction 
without breaking the bank 
the decorators she deals with rarely take the item as shipped 
and use it in a room they further embellish it to make it more 
important for example one decorator created an unusual wall 
hanging from a large piece of burmese embroidered fabric she had 
it stuffed to give it dimension and bring out its interesting 
pattern then mounted it on silk linen and framed it in gold leaf 
before hanging it on a wall 
another decorator chose three colorful 22inch chinese porcelain 
jardinieres she had rosewood bases made for each one set them in 
place in a dining room and then had a oneinch thick glass top made 
to cover them creating a unique dining table 
designers often use antiquities such as etched bronze drums from 
thailand old korean vessels or wedding baskets from indonesia as 
cocktail table bases korean coin chests of a dark wood with iron 
hardware become side tables with storage capacity and coromandel 
screens are turned into cabinet fronts 
