<TEXT>
nearly 75 percent of the nations thrifts already 
meet tougher capital standards proposed in the governments 
multibilliondollar bailout bill according to a study released 
monday 
the study by alex sheshunoff amp co an austinbased consulting 
firm said the findings show that clearly this requirement isnt 
an unbearable burden for the healthy segment of the savings and 
loan industry 
congress is scheduled this week to consider a 157 billion 
bailout bill for the industry which is losing an estimated 20 
million a day among other components the bill requires thrifts to 
have a 3 percent capitaltoassets ratio 
the bill allows half of the capital initially to be in socalled 
goodwill or intangible assets by jan 1 1995 the entire 3 
percent must be in tangible assets 
the bill has been approved by a housesenate conference 
committee but sen phil gramm rtexas has threatened to block 
passage in a dispute over financing 
sheshunoff said his review of the financial status of the 
nations 2946 thrifts found 73 percent or 2163 already meet the 
3 percent core capital requirement contained in the bush 
administrations bailout bill 
in addition sheshunoff said 1984 of the thrifts or 67 
percent can meet the 1995 requirement with tangible assets only 
whie 25 of the nations 40 largest thrifts including 12 of the 
top 13 already meet the 1995 standard the number drops to 12 
including eight of the top 13 if only tangible assets are counted 
sheshunoff said that of the 1984 wellcapitalized sampls the 
average tangible capitaltoassets ratio is 6 percent which puts 
them in a strong position to acquire undercapitalized thrifts 
the difference between the higher interest rates paid by sampls 
for deposits and those paid by banks should narrow sheshunoff 
said of the bailout bill as a result borrowers particularly 
homebuyers may see a decline in interest costs on mortgages 
of the 2163 thrifts with more than 3 percent capital 
sheshunoff said 1886 or 872 percent were profitable of the 783 
that dont meet the 3 percent standard 277 or 354 percent were 
profitable 
sheshunoff based his study on data in the march 31 1989 thrift 
financial reports of the federal home loan bank board 
