taxes raise not just revenues but outrage and 
threats too as well as inspiring wits wags philosophers 
politicians and liars 
will rogers said the tax system generates more liars than the 
game of golf and edmund burke said man can be no more successful 
about taxes than love it goes that way all the way back to the 
greeks and romans 
more currently when the politics of taxation arise some of the 
most extreme claims ever made are heard from taxpayers who 
otherwise stick to the facts 
everyone has heard them the rich live off the taxes of the 
poor the rich pay no taxes the middle class pays most of the 
taxes the poor are taxed disproportionately high 
seeking facts rather than assumptions the nonpartisan tax 
foundation went back through treasury department and internal 
revenue service records and came to this conclusionthe top 
earning half of the population continues to pay well over 90 
percent of the federal individual income tax bill 
in spite of numerous changes in the law the percentage has held 
for at least a decade 
the foundation found that in 1987 43 percent of all federal 
income taxes were paid by the highest 5 percent of taxpayers a 
significant increase from the 376 percent in 1979 more than half 
the taxes were paid by the top 10 percent and almost 77 percent by 
the highest 25 percent based on adjusted gross income 
in contrast the lowest 50 percent paid less than 6 percent of 
taxes in 1987 
the system it concludes remains progressive in fact 
statistics show it might have grown more even more so because the 
lowest half of the income scale paid more than 7 percent of taxes 
in 1979 and less than that in 1987 
that takes care of the rich and poor but what about the 
middleincome class it is in this area that the statistics can do 
an injustice and every person who considers himself or herself to 
be middle class will tell you so 
the main reason for confusion here is the simple phrase or 
more it means that those in the top 5 percent of income are in 
an openended category that ranges all the way from 71125 to 
scores of millions of dollars 
drop down to the next lower category and the point becomes 
clearer those earning 54700 or more paid 554 percent of all 
taxes paid in 1987 but an income of 54700 the foundation 
points out is hardly fat cat status 
it comments it still takes millions of basically middle and 
uppermiddle income taxpayers to pay the bulk of the total income 
tax bill 
but hold on such categories neat and specific though they be 
are really a cause of confusion those making 34260 a year might 
be middleclass statistically but many of them consider themselves 
poor in regard to others 
the term is subjective a recent college graduate still single 
might think 34260 a year is excellent compensation a middleage 
parent funding college tuitions might think it a starvation wage 
for tax purposes almost all people are poor not statistically 
perhaps but certainly in their own minds 
