<TEXT>
contracting for new construction nationwide 
slipped 2 percent in june its second monthly decline led by a 
drop in public works and utilities projects according to a survey 
released monday 
the survey by the fw dodge group of mcgrawhill information 
services co found that overall construction in june declined 2 
percent to an annual rate of 2497 million that followed a 5 
percent decline in may 
public works and utilities construction fell 5 percent in june 
to an annual rate of 436 billion june contracts for new 
nonresidential buildings mainly commercial industrial and 
institutional structures declined 3 percent to 899 billion 
the overdeveloped commercial building market is the achilles 
heel of the construction industry said george a christie the 
groups vice president and chief economist 
despite recent weakening total new construction in the second 
quarter was slightly above that in the first quarter due to aprils 
high rate of contracting fw dodge said 
weve been seeing more than the usual volatility in 
contracting during the first half of 1989 but on balance theres 
been surprisingly little slowdown from the strong 198788 pace of 
building christie said the construction sectors prospects 
for this years second half are good 
 
</TEXT>
