<TEXT>
commodities traders and brokers from the chicago 
board of trade and the chicago mercantile exchange have turned down 
government plea bargain offers a newspaper reported monday 
the 40 traders from the two exchanges are expected to be 
indicted this week on charges of racketeering or mail or wire 
fraud and could face sentences of 30 to 38 months in prison if 
convicted the chicago suntimes reported 
the government team headed by paul coffey the washingtonbased 
deputy chief of the justice departments organized crime and 
racketeering sections also is threatening traders with loss of 
their seats on the exchanges and confiscation of their homes cars 
and other possessions the suntimes said 
the government team proposed a deal to defense lawyers during 
weekend meetings that the traders plead guilty to alleged illegal 
trades and cooperate with prosecutors the newspaper reported 
but the newspaper said lawyers for the traders and brokers 
rejected the government offer while no specific promises were 
made the implication was that the defendants would get better 
treatment if they cooperated the newspaper said 
some defense attorneys said their clients would make restitution 
for the alleged illegal trades but the offers were turned down 
the newspaper reported the report said other lawyers offered to 
have their clients plead guilty to misdemeanors but the government 
insisted on felony charges 
a felony conviction could bar a trader from returning to the 
floor 
a 2year investigation in the case involved undercover federal 
agents placed in the merc and cbot armed with concealed 
microphones the agents focused on the swaggering types and 
people who displayed extravagant lifestyles an unidentified source 
told the newspaper 
us district judge john f grady ruled friday that tapes made 
by agents could be used in the prosecution the recordings took 
place in the exchanges bars restaurants and even restrooms 
sources told the newspaper 
</TEXT>
