<TEXT>
occidental petroleum corp said monday that 
it was again pumping north sea oil a year after 167 men died when 
its piper alpha platform exploded off scotland and half a year 
after it had hoped to resume production 
occidental oil from the alpha claymore and scapa fields in the 
british sector of the north sea had flowed through the huge alpha 
platform which exploded in flames on july 6 1988 and was 
destroyed 
the big oil company said last august that it hoped to resume 
north sea production by the end of the year but it was not until 
saturday that it began pumping oil from the scapa field through the 
claymore platform at about 17000 barrels per day according to the 
announcement monday 
occidental chairman armand hammer said production is expected to 
reach about 100000 barrels per day later this year 
the company said it had installed underwater emergency shutdown 
valves on all platforms leading to and from the claymore platform 
and had taken other safety measures in accordance with industry 
guidelines issued by the united kingdom department of energy 
occidental has offered 187 million in compensation to the 
families of the victims but negotiations continue with their 
attorneys 
occidentals secondquarter earnings announced last week fell 
to 26 million from 78 million in 1988 due in large part to 
exploration and production losses from the north sea disaster 
</TEXT>
